We spend more time reading software than writing software. I never seen any scientific study proving it, but in software field it's like a dogma or a common  belief. Due to it, it's important to try to write software easy to read, it's important to care about the readability of our code. There are some techniques that programmers can use to achieve it. One of them, is write code comments.

We usually write comments to compensate our failure in express our intents through code. Thinking in this way, when we write comments we are not making our code better but we are trying to justify/hide failures in our code. Even worst, there is a relationship between code and comments, for our comments be effective they have to describe what the code does. But wait! 

Software requirements changes and we have to evolve our code to match them and now we have these comments to change too. Sometimes code is difficult to maintain, and we have to remember that code has compilers, unit tests and refactoring tools to give us some help but comments no, comments don't have these tools. Comments frequently become obsolete or orphans and this the reason that I try to avoid write comments, at least bad comments.

<h3><strong>Bad Comments</strong></h3>

Most comments are bad comments and don't have reason to exist. Let me show some.

<strong>Redundant Comments</strong>

Some comments are redundant, they are wrote only to free the programmer's conscience or because the process require it. Look at the example below, this comment don't have reason to exist, the function name/parameters are expressive enough.

<pre>
// Save or Update a entities list
public List<IValidationContainer<T>> SaveOrUpdate(List<T> entities)
{
    var validations = entities.Select(x => x.GetValidationContainer());

    if (validations.All(x => x.IsValid))
    {
        entities.ForEach(x => Repository.SaveOrUpdate(x));
        UnitOfWork.Commit();    
    }

    return validations.ToList();
}
</pre>

It can be even worst:

<pre>
// The person's age
public int Age { get; set; }
</pre>

<strong>Comments substituting a function or variable</strong>

Sometimes we write comments to explain some pieces of our code that could be replaced by a function or variable. Look at this example below.
It's a fake function to print a web page.

<pre>
public void PrintPage()
{
    // print header
    Console.Write("banner");
    Console.Write("menu");

    // print body
    Console.Write("print left sidebar");
    Console.Write("print content");
    Console.Write("print right sidebar");
}
</pre>

The comments are hiding the necessity to extract the prints to a function. We could remove the comments and rewrite it in this way:

<pre>
public void PrintPage()
{
    PrintHeader();
    PrintBody();
}

private static void PrintHeader()
{
    Console.Write("banner");
    Console.Write("menu");
}

private static void PrintBody()
{
    Console.Write("print left sidebar");
    Console.Write("print content");
    Console.Write("print right sidebar");
}
</pre>

<strong>Log Entry</strong>

Some teams add a log entry in the start of a module every time they edit it. These comments contains every change made in the module. Look at this example below.

<pre>
/* Changes (from 11-Oct-2001)
 * --------------------------
 * 11-Oct-2001 : Re-organised the class and moved it to new package 
 * com.jrefinery.date (DG);
 * 05-Nov-2001 : Added a getDescription() method, and eliminated NotableDate
 * class (DG);
 * 12-Nov-2001 : IBD requires setDescription() method, now that NotableDate 
 * class is gone (DG); Changed getPreviousDayOfWeek(), 
 * getFollowingDayOfWeek() and getNearestDayOfWeek() to correct 
 * bugs (DG);
 * 05-Dec-2001 : Fixed bug in SpreadsheetDate class (DG);
 * 29-May-2002 : Moved the month constants into a separate interface 
 * (MonthConstants) (DG);
 */
</pre>

It was acceptable a long time ago when there aren't source control systems. Today this comments are useless and should be avoided.

<strong>Closing Brace Comments</strong>

Sometimes, when we are writing a function that is too big and has a lot of nested structures (like the one below), we, tend to write comments to mark when a block ends. We are doing nothing more than saying to the other developers "I know, this function is so big and messy, I should write smaller ones, but at least I'm helping you to read it!".

<pre>
private ValidationContainer<Task> ExecuteCommand(IEnumerable<ValidationContainer<Task>> validations)
{
    var errors = new Dictionary<string, IList<string>>();

    foreach (var item in validations)
    {
        if (item.IsValid)
        {
            try
            {
                Repository.SaveOrUpdate(item.Entity);
            }
            catch (Exception)
            {
                Console.Write("DB Error");
            }
        } // end if
        else
        {
            return item;
        } // end else
    } // end foreach

    UnitOfWork.Commit();

    return new ValidationContainer<Tarefa>(errors, new Task());
}
</pre>

